### Cybersecurity Overview
- security professionals develop/implement security controls(firewalls, ACLs and encryption(to ensure confidentiality)
- integrity threats may come from attackers or non-malicious sources(power spikes which may corrupt information)
- availability controls include fault tolerance, clustering, and backups
- threats to availability may come from attackers or non-malicious sources(fire destroying a datacenter)
- PII is often protected by regulatory standards
- PII is always governed by ethical considerations
- organizations seek to protect the security of private information
- privacy and security are complementary and overlap(but have different objectives
- (10) GAPP 
  - Management
    - organizations should document privacy practices(in a privacy policy or related document)
  - Notice
    - organizaitons should notify individuals about the privacy practices of the organizaiton and inform them of 'the type of information it collects' and 'how that information is used'
  - Choice and Consent
    - organizations should obtain direct consent from individuals(for stroage, use and sharing of their PII)
  - Collection
    - organizations should collect PII only for 'the purposes identified in the notice and consented to by the individual
  - use, retention, and disposal
    - organizations should only use information for identified purposes, may not use information collected for any non-disclosed purpose
  - access
    - organizations should provide individuals with access to any PII collecte din the organizations records, at the individuals request
  - disclosure
    - organizations will disclose information to third parties(only when consistent with notice and consent)
  - security
    - PII confidentiality will be protected
  - quality
    - PII integrity will be protected
  - monitoring and enforcement
    - organizations will put business processes in place to ensure compliance
- privacy laws require implementation of several GAPPs(in some jurisdictions and industries)

### Evaluating Security Risks
- risk analysis is the 'cornerstone of information security'
- analysts must understand their technological environment and external threats to the security of their information
- risk assessment combines information about internal/external factors. Helps analysts understand threats facing their organization and design control sets to handle threats
- Example:
  - Web server running outdated version of Apache service
    - may contain vulnerability(that would allow a DoS attack against the websites hosted on the web server)
    - availability risk
    - can be remediated by upgrading Apache service(to the most recent version(assuming that is not susceptible to this type of DoS vulnerability)
  - Bad actor attempting to conduct a DoS attack against a website that has a known vulnerability due to out-of-date Apache services
    - poses a threat to the availability of the web service
  - Bad actor targets an organizations web sever with a DoS attack, but the server was patched
    - server is no longer 'vulnerable to this attack'
    - there is NO risk(even though a threat is present), because there is no vulnerability
  - Datacenter may be vulnerable to the damage caused by an earthquake(due to the walls not being built to withstand extreme movements), but the datacenter is located in a region where earthquakes are rare
    - the datacenter is vulnerable 
    - there is no plausible threat 
    - since there is a vulnerability but no threat, then there is no risk
- threats may or may not be malicious in nature
- natural disasters are threats to availability(may cause damage to equipment that hosts essential services)
- security cannot do much to eliminate natural disaster threats
- organizations should routinely conduct risk assessment
- NIST publishes a guide for conducting risk assessments(widely used throughout the cybersecurity field as a foundation for (RA)
  - NIST SP 800-30
  - suggests an organization should identify threats/vulnerabilities
  - use 'that information' to determine 'level of posed risk'

### Identify Threats
- organizations begin risk assessment by identifying 'types of threats that exist in their threat environment'
- malware and spam are threats to all organizations
- some threats are targeted against specific types of organizations
  - government-sponsored APT attacks
    - target goverment agencies, military organizations, companies that may operate in related fields
    - unlikely to target an elementary school
- NIST identifies (4) categories of threats faced by organizations that should be considered in their threat identification
- Adversaries may include: trusted insiders, competitors , suppliers, customers, business partners, or nation-states
- analysts should consider: capability of the threat actor(s) to engage in attacks, intent of the threat actor(s), likelihood that they will target your organization, the possible range of effects that a threat may have on your organization, common natural environmental threats to their geographic region, how to appropriately prevent/counter human-made environmental threats
- system admins may accidentally delete critical disk volumes
  - may cause loss of availability
- structural threats may come from IT componenets(storage, servers, network devices), environmental controls(power and cooling infrastructure), software(OS and apps), 
- environmental threats include fires, flooding, storms, power failures, widespread telecommunication disruptions
- nature/scope of threats vary(depending on the nature of the organization, composition of its tech infrastructure, and situation-specific circumstances)
- it may be helpful to obtain copies of risk assessments performed by similar organizations(as a starting point)

### Identify Vulnerabilities
